%N A118800 Triangle read by rows: T satisfies the matrix products: C*T*C = T^-1 and T*C*T = C^-1, where C is Pascal's triangle.
%C A118800 The matrix square, T^2, consists of columns that are all the same.
%C A118800 Matrix inverse is triangle A118801. Row sums form {0^n, n>=0}.
%C A118800 Unsigned row sums equal A025192(n) = 2*3^(n-1), n>=1.
%C A118800 Row squared sums equal A051708.
%C A118800 Antidiagonal sums equals all 1's.
%C A118800 Unsigned antidiagonal sums form A078057 (with offset).
%C A118800 Antidiagonal squared sums form A002002(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} C(n,k+1)*C(n+k,k), n>=1.
%C A118800 From _Paul Barry_, Nov 10 2008: (Start)
%C A118800 T is [1,1,0,0,0,...] DELTA [ -1,0,0,0,0,...] or C(1,n) DELTA -C(0,n). (DELTA defined in A084938).
%C A118800 The positive matrix T_p is [1,1,0,0,0,...] DELTA [1,0,0,0,0,...]. T_p*C^-1 is
%C A118800 [0,1,0,0,0,....] DELTA [1,0,0,0,0,...] which is C(n-1,k-1) for n,k>=1. (End)
%C A118800 The triangle formed by deleting the minus signs is the mirror of the self-fusion of Pascal's triangle; see Comments at A081277 and A193722. - _Clark Kimberling_, Aug 04 2011
%C A118800 Riordan array ( (1 - x)/(1 - 2*x), -x/(1 - 2*x) ). Cf. A209149. The matrix square is the Riordan array ( (1 - x)^2/(1 - 2*x), x ), which belongs to the Appell subgroup of the Riordan group. See the Example section below. - _Peter Bala_, Jul 17 2013
%C A118800 From _Peter Bala_, Feb 23 2019: (Start)
%C A118800 There is a 1-parameter family of solutions to the simultaneous equations C*T*C = T^-1 and T*C*T = C^-1, where C is Pascal's triangle. Let T(k) denote the Riordan array ( (1 - k*x)/(1 - (k + 1)*x), -x/(1 - (k + 1)*x) ) so that T(1) = T. Then C*T(k)*C = T(k)^-1 and T(k)*C*T(k) = C^-1, for arbitrary k. For arbitrary m, the Riordan arrays (T(k)*C^m)^2 and (C^m*T(k))^2 both belong to the Appell subgroup of the Riordan group.
%C A118800 More generally, given a fixed m, we can ask for a lower triangular array X solving the simultaneous equations (C^m)*X*(C^m) = X^-1 and X*(C^m)*X = C^(-m). A 1-parameter family of solutions is given by the Riordan arrays X = ( (1 - m*k*x)/(1 - m*(k + 1)*x), -x/(1 - m*(k + 1)*x) ). The Riordan arrays X^2 , (X*C^n)^2 and (C^n*X)^2, for arbitrary n, all belong to the Appell subgroup of the Riordan group. (End)
%H A118800 Paul D. Hanna, <a href="/A118800/b118800.txt">Rows 0..45 of triangle, flattened.</a>
%H A118800 Florian Luca, Attila Pethő, and László Szalay, <a href="https://nyjm.albany.edu/j/2021/27-44.html">Duplications in the k-generalized Fibonacci sequences</a>, New York J. Math. (2021) Vol. 27, 1115-1133.
%F A118800 T(n,k) = (-1)^k * 2^(n-k) * ( C(n,k) + C(n-1,k-1) )/2 for n>=k>=0 with T(0,0) = 1. Antidiagonals form the coefficients of Chebyshev polynomials: T(n,k) = [x^(2*n)] [(1+sqrt(1-x^2))^(n+k) + (1-sqrt(1-x^2))^(n+k)]/2.
%F A118800 Rows of the triangle are generated by taking successive iterates of (A135387)^n * [1, 1, 0, 0, 0, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 09 2007
%F A118800 O.g.f.: (1 - t)/(1 + t*(x - 2)) = 1 + (1 - x)*t + (2 - 3*x + x^2)^t^2 + (4 - 8*x + 5*x^2 - x^3)*t^3 + ....  Row polynomial R(n,x) = (1 - x)*(2 - x)^(n-1) for n >= 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jul 17 2013
%F A118800 T(n,k)=2*T(n-1,k)-T(n-1,k-1) with T(0,0)=T(1,0)=1, T(1,1)=-1, T(n,k)=0 if k<0 or if k>n. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 25 2013
%F A118800 G.f. for row n (n>=1): Sum_{k=0..n} T(n,k)*x^k = (1-x)*(2-x)^(n-1). - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 25 2013
%F A118800 From _Tom Copeland_, Nov 15 2016: (Start)
%F A118800 E.g.f. is [1 + (1-x)e^((2-x)t)]/(2-x), so the row polynomials are p_n(x) = (1-q,(x))^n, umbrally, where (q.(x))^k = q_k(x) are the row polynomials of A239473, or, equivalently, T = M*A239473, where M is the inverse Pascal matrix C^(-1) = A130595 with the odd rows negated, i.e., M(n,k) = (-1)^n C^(-1)(n,k) with e.g.f. exp[(1-x)t]. Cf. A200139: A200139(n,k) = (-1)^k* A118800(n,k).
%F A118800 TCT = C^(-1) = A130595 and A239473 = A000012*C^(-1) = S*C^(-1) imply (M*S)^2 = Identity matrix, i.e., M*S = (M*S)^(-1) = S^(-1)*M^(-1) = A167374*M^(-1). Note that M = M^(-1). Cf. A097805. (End)
